\begin_layout Subsection
Limitations and solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{showtext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is to provide an elegant way to allow R using system fonts in graphics.
 While it should be useful in most situations, there are probably two major
 limitations that can be hard to overcome.
 This section lists these cons of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{showtext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, as well as some hints of how to use it in the best way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{showtext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 looks for fonts according to their filenames rather than the usual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

font names
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the system.
 This design is intentional since font name can be ambiguous, e.g., the same
 font can have multiple names given by different font management software.
 In contrast, font file is the entity that actually contains the glyphs
 of a specific font, hence it helps to avoid such confusion.
 While this setting may cause some problems for users who are searching
 the filename for the first time, it should be quite convenient afterwards,
 and one possible solution is to use the fonts in Google Fonts through function
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{font.add.google()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which maintains a standard and stable interface to access fonts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{showtext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can produce poor-quality graphs on certain bitmap graphics devices, such
 as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{png()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{jpeg()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{tiff()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{showtext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is in effect transforming character glyphs into paths (described in more
 detail in the next section), and those devices do not support anti-alias
 feature, resulting in unsmooth edges of the characters.
 If bitmap is needed, it is strongly recommended to use the devices provided
 by the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{Cairo}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 package, such as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{CairoPNG()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{CairoJPEG()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, etc., which support such features and hence are able to produce high quality
 output.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pkg{showtext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 works well on vector graphics devices, including 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{pdf()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{svg()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
code{postscript()}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, since most reader software of these formats will take care of the graphics
 rendering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
